**Let's Start:-**
1. We know, for every bit position, numbers are lying in a certain range and they form the arithmetic progression
2. Example:- bit position 0:- (1-1,3-3,5-5,7-7...and so on).
3. Example bit position1 :- (2-3,6-7,10-11,14-15... and so on).
4. Example bit position 2:- (4-7,12-15,20-23,28-31 and so on).
5. Example bit position 3:- (8-15,24-31,40-47,56-63 and so on).
....so on.
Hence, we will work on every bit position and since we need to focus on bitwise AND, so numbers in the range [left,right], if they all have 1 at current bit position, **we'll include (1<<i) into our answer.**

**Wait:-**  How we'll check ?
**Idea?:-**  We'll find our interval which is closest to [left and right] and check [left,right] completely lies inside our interval [l1,r1] then, we're done...we'll include (1<<i) into our answer since we know [l1,r1] will contain all 1s at current bit position.

**How to find [l1,r1]:-** For every bit position...left bound of interval follows the Arithmetic Progression...Hence you can easily find the interval closest to [left, right]. **I expect, you can do further mathematical calculations since you passed class 10th right (XD) ?**

**If you find the Post Helpful, Do give me upvotes!**

```
class Solution {
public:
    #define ll long long
    int rangeBitwiseAnd(int left, int right) {
        ll ans = 0;
        for(ll i=0;i<=30;i++){
            ll a = (1LL<<i);
            ll l = left - a,p = l/(a*2);
            ll l1 = p*a*2 + a,r1 = l1 + a - 1;
            if(left>=l1 and right<=r1)
                ans+=a;
        }
        return (int)ans;
    }
};
```

