The idea to iterate over all the elements from left to right is not a good one, instead I suggest something better than this. 
If we can get the "Common Bit Prefix" of left and right, that itself is our answer.
For Example, let us consider: left = 357 and right = 366
Using Binary representation, (only 9 bits represented and other 21 bits are all 0's )
left     = 101100101
right   = 101101110
The common prefix is " 10110 " so the answer will be 256+0+64+32+0 = 352 .
The above idea holds true because there always exists a number between left and right, such that after the first prefix mismatching bit in left and right, all the other combinations of 0's and 1's after the mismatching bit are covered by the numbers between left and right and the Bitwise AND of the range results in low ( 0 ) if any of the numbers between left and right is low ( 0 ) for that particular bit.
```
class Solution { 
public:                                    
    int rangeBitwiseAnd(int left, int right) { 
        //Finding the Common Prefix of left and right is the answer
        int ans=0;
        for(int bit=30;bit>=0;bit--){
            // To check for a specific bit number
            if((left&(1<<bit))!=(right&(1<<bit)))
                break; //Not Common: so no need to check further
            else
                ans|=(left&(1<<bit)); //Common: add the value of specific bit and continue 
        }
        return ans;
    }
};

