My logic works on the principle that if any 2^x`[x is an int]` is present in the range, excluding m, then the value will be 0.
As in, between 5 and 10, there is 8 `[2^3]` which corresponds to `1000` in binary. when this happens, the bitwise AND with its previous number will always yield 0.

Now to find that number, take m and find it's` result = log base 2(m)`. Check if `2^(result+1) <= n`. 

Otherwise do normal bitwise operation.

    private static long getLogBase2(int a) {
        return (long)(Math.log(a)/Math.log(2));
    }    
    public int rangeBitwiseAnd(int m, int n) {
        if (m == 0) return 0;
        long nextVal = getLogBase2(m);
        if (Math.pow(2, nextVal + 1) <= n) return 0;

        long value = m;
