**ATLAST we see: for [a,b] a&b<=min(a,b)**
At the first glance, looping from m to n seems straightforward but obviously time limit exceeds.
Iterating from m to n seems unavailable, but we can consider looping from bit to bit.
(works good for nos of 2^31 range)(save sis from runtime error)
Let's first write down some binary numbers:
1    000001
2    000010
3    000011
4    000100
5    000101
6    000110
7    000111
8    001000
As we can see,every consecutive numbers lowest bit(LSB) is either 1 or 0.So,doing '&' operation over consecutive nos results 0 or 1 in LSB positon.
So,if there are nos between given range[m,n],LSB will be 0 after & operation.
So,for every bit from LSB to MSB,we shift both and compare them,if(n>m) then some nos are between them,so lowest bit now in answer will be 0.
Again we go on shifting until we reach equality.
After equality, answer bits will be same as any one of them(since 0&0 =0,1&1 =1).
We can see it from below example..

m =  01000
n =   01011

(1)   01011 > 01000  ->  lowest bit = 0
(2)   0101 > 0100      ->  2nd lowest bit  = 0
(3)   010 = 010          ->  3rd lowest bit = current lowest bit  0
(4)   01 = 01              ->  4th lowest bit = current lowest bit   1
(5)   0 = 0                  ->  5th lowest bit = current lowest bit   0

Final result:   01000
**We can see that step (3)-(5) is unnecessary, when m=n, the other bits are just the same as current m (or n), then we can easily get the final result.**

Finally, incurred from this is
for range [a,b];
a&b<=min(a,b);
