When the bit is different, then for bitwise AND we get 0. Continue this until two numbers match.
Now, the final result could be obtained when we shift the first number (which is less than the other) to that many bits to the left. Because the rest of the bits are zero.
**For example** - 1001 - 1011

			Iteration 1 -> 
								0100, 0101
								-> 0010, 0010
			Total dropped -> 2
			Result -> 
								0010 << 2 -> 1000 (8)
			This is the bitwise AND of 9 to 11.

```java
public int rangeBitwiseAnd(int m, int n) {
	if (m == n) return m;
	if (m == 0 || n == 0) return 0;

	int droppedBitCount = 0;

	while (m != n) {
		m = m >> 1;
		n = n >> 1;
		droppedBitCount++;
	}
	return m << droppedBitCount;
}

