solutions.content:
My intuition took me to somewhere else rather than other solutions.

**Intuition:**
* If numbers (m and n) are in different power of twos, then it means that the result is 0 every time.
* Else if numbers are in the same power of two then it means that the first bit is countable and we will check rest bits with recursion. 

**Let me explain with examples:**

```
13 - 001101
14 - 001110
15 - 001111
16 - 010000 <- it will change all bits to 0. (Look at example 1)
17 - 010001
18 - 010010
19 - 010011
20 - 010100 <- 3rd and 5th bits are 1 (Look at example 2)
21 - 010101
22 - 010111 <- 3rd and 5th bits are 1
23 - 011000
```

1. Example 1) `(m, n) = (14, 19)`. In this case, as I mentioned before, 16 (010000) will change all bits to 0 and that is why the result is 0. Surely this approach works for all such where m and n are in different power of twos. 

1. Example 2) `(m, n) = (20, 22)`. As the power of 2s are the same we should add the power of two of current number to result and traverse all rest of bits. 

**Java:**
```java
public int rangeBitwiseAnd(int m, int n) {        
	int pm = log2(m);
	int pn = log2(n);

	if (m == 0 || n == 0 || pm != pn) {                         // if logarithms of numbers are different
		return 0;
	} 

	int newm = 1 << pm;                                         // adding number to result 
	return newm + rangeBitwiseAnd(m & (newm-1), n & (newm-1));  // unsetting first bits of both m and n 
}

private int log2(int a) {
	return (int) (Math.log(a) / Math.log(2));
}
```

