solutions.content:
The idea is to go through the all bits and check if it present in both numbers and if this bit is not larger then the difference `n-m`. 

So in first `while` we discard all bits that are less than `n-m`, because if it is so - it means that on the way from `m` to `n` that bit will change at least once.

In the next `while` we append all bits that are present in both numbers and larger than difference, so it means they won't change on that way. 

We can stop when our bit is larger than `m`, because all the next bits won't be present in `m`.

```
class Solution {
    public int rangeBitwiseAnd(int m, int n) {
        int d = n - m;
        int res = 0;
        long p = 1;
        while (p <= m && p <= d) { p = p << 1; }
        while (p <= m) {
            if ((p&n) != 0 && (p&m) != 0) res |= p;
            p = p << 1;
        }
        return res;
    }
}
```

