2 things to consider
1. if the 2 numbers are equal, then their Binary representations are equal. so return the number.
2. We need to keep chopping off the LSB, ie. so we keep right shifting until `m` becomes equal to `n`.

When it does become equal, we left shift either m or n, step times to the left, and return the resultant value.

```
public int rangeBitwiseAnd(int m, int n) {

        //********************
        int ans = 0;
        int step = 0;
        while (m != n) {
            //we need to keep chopping off the lsb
            m = m >>> 1;
            n = n >>> 1;
            step++;
        }
        ans = m << step;
        return ans;
    }
```

