The 2nd bit was unset 0-3, set from 4-7, unset 8-11, and will be set again 12-15, changing every 4 numbers
So if the difference between m and n is greater than 4, we know that there must be at least one number such that the 2nd bit is unset
Otherwise, we must check both the k'th bit in m and the k'th bit in n to see if it was unset in either one
```
class Solution {
public:
    int rangeBitwiseAnd(int m, int n) {
        bitset<31>res(INT_MAX),x(m),y(n);
        for(int i=0;i<32;++i){
            if(n-m>(1<<i) || x[i]==0 || y[i]==0)res[i]=0;
        }   
        return (int)(res.to_ulong());
    }
};
```

