You might find it easier to understand the third solution by switching the while condition as follows:

```
class Solution {
    public int rangeBitwiseAnd(int m, int n) {
        while ((m & n) != n) {
            n &= n - 1;
        }
        return n;
    }
}
```

The idea is that we keep turning off the least significant bit set to 1 in `n` until `m & n` is equal to `n`.

* When `m & n` is equal to `n`, we will have found the longest common prefix between `m` and `n`, and it will be `n`.
* If there is no such common prefix, `n` will eventually be 0, causing the loop to termiate and the function to return `0`.

