# Approach 1->
basic approach is to loop from m to n and keep on doing bitwise &. But it takes o(n) time.
```
public int rangeBitwiseAnd(int left, int right) {
    if(left==right) {
        return left;
    }
    int res = left;
    for (int i = left + 1; i < right; i++) {
        if (res == 0) {
            return 0;
        }
        res = res & i;
    }
    return res & right;
}
```
# Approach 2-> using some bits observation. 
1.We can do it faster just by observing some property of bit.
3.	right shift by 1 will remove last digit from binary representation of number
4.	left shift by 1 will add 0 after last digit in binary representation of number
5.	**Example 1**-> Suppose m=16 and n=19 ->
M=10000
N =10011
Numbers are – 
10000
10001
10010
10011 
Result =        10000
It is clear that if we go from left to right (i.e. from MSB to LSB) for m and n only. The common digits will be in the result and remaining digit will be zero in result.
10000 and 10011 has 100 common and after that we have two digits left so we append two 0 at end. So result will be 10000.
**Example 2**->
m = 00110
n = 11111
here there is no common digit from left to right. hence answer will be 0
**Example 3**->
m = 110001
n = 111011
here common digit is 11. hence answer will be 110000
6.	So, now problem is to find common digits from left to right. We can do it by performing right shift of m and n till m and n are same. And keep counter to count number of shift done.
So, we get 100 whose decimal value is 4 and now if we do left shift of this 4 by count number of times. We get the result. As left shift will append zero to result count number of times.

Maximum time below while loop will run is 32. which is fixed irrepective how range will grow.
hence time complexity is constant.
```
public int rangeBitwiseAnd(int m, int n) {
        int c=0;
        while(m!=n){
            m=m>>1;
            n=n>>1;
            c++;
        }
        return m<<c;
    }
```

