solutions.content:
This was a nice path to further and further improvements.

First we set up 2 pointers, `i` and `j`, like [in the base problem](https://leetcode.com/discuss/topic/770505), so check there for some discussion about why we start from beginning and end, instead of starting from the center (spoiler: just easier to visualise/conceive, plus no need for extra logic depending on whether or not the string has an odd length).

And like the previous problem we progress, BUT when we find a mismatch, the things turn funny and I opted to return the result of the function called on the rest of the string skipping the next position of `i` or the next position of `j` - notice I also added a boolean flag `del` to mark whether or not we did our trial with a deletion: it defaults to `false`, and then of course it get turned to `true` in the recursive calls with the rest of the string.

If we exit our loop safely, then we just return `true` :)

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    bool validPalindrome(string s, bool del = false) {
        int i = -1, j = s.size();
        while (i++ < j--) {
            if (s[i] != s[j]) {
                return !del && (validPalindrome(s.substr(i, j - i), true) || validPalindrome(s.substr(i + 1, j - i), true));
            }
        }
        return true;
    }
};
```

After the improvements, removing the `.substr` part did not gain much, but turning `s` into `&s` (ie: passing it by reference) did wonders for the performances, particularly space related (of course!).

The improved code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    bool validPalindrome(string s, bool del = false, int i = -1, int j = -1) {
        if (j == - 1) j = s.size();
        while (i++ < j--) {
            if (s[i] != s[j]) {
                return !del && (validPalindrome(s, true, i - 1, j) || validPalindrome(s, true, i, j + 1));
            }
        }
        return true;
    }
};
```

A nice exercise now would be to turn it into a recursive function, but I am too bored by this problem for now to do it :)

