# My Submition
![important.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/f74c7568-6383-4805-8474-571cbae5a5d0_1675001959.0578392.png)

# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
So my first thought is why don't we use a **Hash Table** to store the values and we can check if there are more than two characters which aren't duplicated then we will return **false** otherwise we will return **true**. 
That's not going to work because these characters might be in the beginning or the end and that will make the string not palindrome. 

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
So my approach in this problem is that i will use two pointers so that we can check if the string is palindrome after execluding one of the **chars**. 

If the `s[left] == s[right]` then we will increase the left pointer and decrease the right pointer, otherwise we will execlude one of the chars at the two pointers.

After execluding the character from the **left pointer** then we have to check if all the remaining **chars** are palindrom or not, as well as we will do the same after execluding the right pointer.


# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
public class Solution {
    public bool ValidPalindrome(string s) {
        int left = 0, right = s.Length - 1;

        while (left < right){
            if (s[left] == s[right]){
                left++;
                right--;
            }else 
                return IsPalindrome(s, left + 1, right) || IsPalindrome(s, left, right - 1);     
        }

        return true;
    }
    private bool IsPalindrome(string s, int left, int right){
        while (left < right){
            if (s[left] != s[right])
                return false;
            left++;
            right--;
        }
        return true;
    }
}
```

