solutions.content:
In regular palindrome check, you can use a two pointer approach, i.e. p1 goes from begining to end and p2 vice versa and each time you check: ``` s[p1] == s[p2] ```
Its a similar idea here, except when you reach the first occurance of different character, you have to decide which character you should remove? You have to consider both cases, if any of them works, then it is a correct answer.

```
    // Scan the array, look for the first occurance
    // of where the characters are not equal, like this: "z****k"
    // then here we have two choices, either to remove 'z', so to evaluate the "****k" string
    // or remove 'k' and evaluate the "z****" string

    bool isPalindrome(string s, int p1, int p2) {
        while(p1 < p2) {
            if(s[p1] == s[p2]) {
                ++p1;
                --p2;
            } else
                return false;
        }
        return true;
    }

	// Time: O(N), Space: O(1)
    bool validPalindrome(string s) {

        int p1 = 0;
        int p2 = s.size() - 1;

        while(p1 < p2) {
            if(s[p1] != s[p2]) {

                // Either remove the character in p1 (so move p1 to p1 + 1)
                // or remvoe the character in p2 (so move p2 to p2 - 1)
				// if any of these two cases forms a palindrom, it is still a correct answer
                bool case1 = isPalindrome(s, p1 + 1, p2);
                bool case2 = isPalindrome(s, p1, p2 - 1);
                return case1 || case2;

            } else {
                ++p1;
                --p2;
            }
        }
        return true;
    }
```

