solutions.content:
After one read of this problem the first impression was to do simple pallindrome check with an exception that we are allowed at 1 mismatch.

So the intital thought process was (which was incorrect):

1) Intitalize start=0 and end=size-1.
2) If the elements at start and end are equal then increment start and decrement end.
3) Otherwise maintain a flag to keep a check on threshold (i.e 1 mismatch). If threshold not exceeded: 
	3.1)  Check if (s[ start+1] and s[end]) are same if yes then  continue the loop  from[start+1,end].
	3.2) Otherwise if (s[start] and s[end-1]) are same then continue the loop from [start,end-1].
	3.3) Otherwise return false.
4) If we have exceeded threshold we return false.

This was the first code i came up with:

```
bool validPalindrome(string s) {

        int size=s.size();
        int start=0,end=size-1;
		bool thresh=false; // showing that threshold not reached

        while(start<end){
            if(s[start]==s[end]){
                start++;
                end--;
            }

            else if(!thresh){ // if we have first mismatch

                if(s[start+1]==s[end]){
                    start++; // continue the while loop from [start+1,end]
                    thresh=true; // one mismatch seen
                }

                else if(s[end-1]==s[start]){
                    end--; // continue the while loop from [start,end-1]
                    thresh=true; // one mismatch seen
                }

                else{  // neither of the two [start+1,end] or [start,end-1] are same
                    return false;
                }
            }

            else{  // 2nd mismatch
                return false;
            }
        }

        return true;
    }

```

This passed 458 of the 460 test cases, but the test case which failed kind of annoyed me because:

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/d477eef6-d3de-45c4-acdd-5f935bf5f005_1614877680.708844.png)

a 100 sized string.....  How on earth could I debug for this case.

So after a long brainstorm, a friend of mine suggested a case where my code will fail: **s="adccdca".**

why?		
when at start=1 (1st d from left) and end=5(1st c from right) we were checking if s[start+1]==s[end] ? yes so continue from [2,5] which is "ccdc" string and this is not a pallindrome (as threshold is exhausted).
Instead from [1,4] which is "dccd" is a pallindrome.

**Conclusion** - At the mismatch we need to check string from both [start+1,end] and [start,end-1] and if any one them is pallindrome we return true. 

So finally the correct version:

```
    bool validPalindrome(string s) {

        int size=s.size();
        int start=0,end=size-1,count=0;

        while(start<end){

            if(s[start]==s[end]){
                start++;
                end--;
            }

            else{

                int first_start=start+1,first_end=end; // if start is deleted
                int second_start=start,second_end=end-1; // if end is deleted

				// check pallindrome from start+1 to end
                while(first_start<first_end && s[first_start]==s[first_end]){ 
                    first_start++;
                    first_end--;
                }

				// check pallindrome from start to end-1
                while(second_start<second_end && s[second_start]==s[second_end]){ /
                    second_start++;
                    second_end--;
                }

                return ((first_start>=first_end) || (second_start>=second_end));  // if anyone of the two scans are complete 
            }
        }
        // the whole string is pallindrome
        return true;
    }

```

Ps - In my opinion an easy question though but the test cases are poor (an easier TC could have been provided to show the failiure of trivial solution). 

Hope this helps!!!

